message.content:
 You can align a row of `div` elements to the right using CSS Flexbox by setting the parent container's display property to `flex`, and then applying these properties:

1. Set the `justify-content` property to `flex-end`. This will align the content at the end of the container (i.e., to the right).
2. Set the `align-items` property to `center`. This will vertically center the elements within the container.

Here's an example:

HTML:
```html
<div class="container">
  <div>Div 1</div>
  <div>Div 2</div>
  <div>Div 3</div>
</div>
```
CSS:
```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
  align-items: center;
}

.container div {
  margin: 10px;
  padding: 20px;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  border-radius: 5px;
}
```
This will result in the following output:

![Example of aligned right divs](https://i.imgur.com/L3XDx4C.png)

In this example, the container has three `div` elements inside it, and they are aligned to the right (end) side of the container and vertically centered.
